{{Too much detail|section|date=September 2024|reason=A ''few'' totals at different dates, some of the charges (arson, attacking police, encouragement on social media, ...) and perhaps some particularly noteworthy cases (boys and girls from 11 years old, serving military, ...) are all that is needed in a reference work - not a newspaper.}}|section=y}}
On 3 August, the Ministry of Justice (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Justice began discussions about Magistrates' court (England and Wales)|magistrates' courts in England and Wales remaining open overnight to preliminary rule on suspects arrested, due to the anticipated increase in people held in custody for riot related offences. This also occurred during the 2011 England riots. This proposal was criticised by Nazir Afzal, a former Chief Crown Prosecutor, saying such a measure would worsen the backlog in British courts.
